const Q = [
  { id:1, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"When creating a Free-Form Report, which types of visualizations are available for you to include?",
    opts:["Line charts, bar charts, histograms, and geo maps","Tables, line charts, circle charts, and donut charts","Pie charts, donut charts, geo maps, and circle charts","Tables, line charts, scatterplots, and bar charts"],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Free-form visualizations:</strong> Table (default), Donut Chart, Line Chart, Scatterplot, Bar Chart, and Geo Map. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> 'Histograms' are not a native option. 'Circle chart' is not GA4 terminology — the correct term is 'Donut chart.'" },

  { id:2, cat:"Data Collection",
    q:"You have a website and want to start gathering and reporting insights for it in Google Analytics. What should you set up first?",
    opts:["Analytics SDK","Analytics tag","Firebase SDK","Google Ads"],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>Analytics tag (gtag.js)</strong> is a code snippet placed on website pages so GA4 can start collecting data. After creating a GA4 property and web data stream, you receive a 'G-' ID and global site tag to install. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> SDKs are for mobile apps. Google Ads is a separate platform — linking it happens after tracking is set up." },

  { id:3, cat:"Data Collection",
    q:"Which of these features lets you control how long user-level and event-level data is stored by Google Analytics?",
    opts:["Disable data collection","IP address settings","Consent Mode","Data retention period"],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Data retention period</strong> sets how long GA4 stores granular user-level and event-level data. Standard: 2 months or 14 months. GA4 360: up to 50 months. Primarily affects Explorations and Funnel reports. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> 'Disable' stops all tracking. IP settings anonymize IPs. Consent Mode adjusts tag behavior based on consent status." },

  { id:4, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"Which new report template should you use to create a net-new report detailing source / medium filtered to desktop users only?",
    opts:["Use the Tech Details template.","Use the Traffic Acquisition template.","Use the Demographic Details template.","Use the Landing Page template."],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>Traffic Acquisition</strong> is the primary home for Source / Medium data. Workflow: Library → Create new report → Traffic Acquisition → add filter (Device category = desktop) → save → add to a Collection. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Tech Details focuses on browser/OS. Demographics shows user attributes. Landing Page shows entry pages, not sources." },

  { id:5, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"When you view a User Acquisition Report and a Traffic Acquisition Report, what are the key differences?",
    opts:["User Acquisition shows the first campaign/source/medium of the session; Traffic Acquisition shows the last touch.","Traffic Acquisition shows the very first source the user arrived with; User Acquisition shows the session source.","User Acquisition shows the very first source the user arrived with; Traffic Acquisition shows the session source.","Traffic Acquisition uses data-driven attribution; User Acquisition shows the last touch."],
    ans:2,
    exp:"<strong>User Acquisition (User-scoped):</strong> Tracks how a user discovered your brand for the very first time — always attributes to that original 'First user source' regardless of later visits. <br><br><strong>Traffic Acquisition (Session-scoped):</strong> Credits each individual session's source separately — if a user visits via email then later via paid ad, each session gets its own credit." },

  { id:6, cat:"Events, Audiences & Conversions",
    q:"Which Google Analytics feature relies on machine learning and Google AI for measuring conversions that can't be spotted through direct observation?",
    opts:["The Conversion events feature","The Attribution paths feature","The Key event modeling feature","The Conversion window feature"],
    ans:2,
    exp:"<strong>Key event modeling</strong> uses machine learning to fill conversion gaps caused by declined cookie consent, browser ITP, or cross-device movement. GA's AI analyzes observed user patterns to estimate outcomes for unobserved users. (Renamed from 'Conversions' to 'Key Events' in March 2024.) <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Conversion events feature = manual toggle. Attribution paths = reporting tool. Conversion window = a timing lookback setting." },

  { id:7, cat:"Integrations & APIs",
    q:"This Analytics feature allows you to connect individual customers' behavior across various interactions on different platforms and devices by letting you associate your own identifiers.",
    opts:["Device-ID","Audience triggers","Predictive audiences","User-ID"],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>User-ID</strong> lets you send your own unique, non-PII identifier (e.g., hashed login ID) to GA4 when a user signs in. Because the ID is tied to the person (not the device), GA4 recognizes the same user across devices and platforms. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Device-ID is browser/hardware-specific. Audience triggers fire events when criteria are met. Predictive audiences forecast future behavior." },

  { id:8, cat:"Integrations & APIs",
    q:"Which Google Analytics feature would allow you to develop a dashboard to view analytics data alongside in-store customer purchase data that lives in another business application?",
    opts:["The Data API feature","The Admin API feature","The Firebase SDK feature","The Measurement Protocol feature"],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Measurement Protocol</strong> allows you to send data directly to GA4 servers via HTTP requests from any internet-connected device (like a POS system or CRM). It bridges offline transactions with online behavior for a complete cross-channel dashboard. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Data API reads data out of GA. Admin API manages settings. Firebase SDK tracks mobile apps only." },

  { id:9, cat:"Advanced & 360",
    q:"Which Analytics 360 feature would you use to filter data and create a new dataset for a specific use case or audience?",
    opts:["Organizations","Roll-up properties","Subproperties","Data streams"],
    ans:2,
    exp:"<strong>Subproperties (360 only)</strong> take a 'Source Property' and filter its data into a separate focused dataset — e.g., only North American users. They have their own access controls, settings, and can link to their own Google Ads accounts. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Roll-up properties aggregate multiple sources (opposite of filtering). Data streams are data collection pipes. Organizations manage billing/users." },

  { id:10, cat:"Events, Audiences & Conversions",
    q:"Some of the events on your website are especially valuable — like purchases or newsletter sign-ups. If you wanted to mark these events as important and assign a value to them, what mark should you assign?",
    opts:["You should mark them as Recommended events.","You should mark them as Custom events.","You should mark them as Automatic events.","You should mark them as Key events."],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Key events</strong> (formerly 'Conversions') are how GA4 tracks high-value actions. Marking an event as Key unlocks Key event rate metrics, allows monetary value assignment, and aligns with Google Ads terminology for Smart Bidding. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Recommended events = Google templates (don't become important automatically). Custom events = self-defined events that are still regular until toggled. Automatic events = out-of-the-box basics." },

  { id:11, cat:"Explorations & Analysis",
    q:"When building a purchase funnel in Explore, which of these dimensions allow you to select a homepage view?",
    opts:["Page type allows you to select a homepage view.","Homepage name allows you to select a homepage view.","Purchase allows you to select a homepage view.","Page path and screen class allow you to select a homepage view."],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Page path and screen class</strong> is the standard dimension for specific URLs. The homepage = <code>/</code> in Page path. Filter: 'page path exactly matches /'. You can also use 'Page title and screen name' if the homepage has a unique title, but page path is more reliable. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> 'Page type' requires a custom dimension. 'Homepage name' is not a GA4 dimension. 'Purchase' is an event, not a page identifier." },

  { id:12, cat:"Data Collection",
    q:"You're asked to set up a data stream in accordance with setting up Google Analytics. What is a data stream?",
    opts:["A data stream lives within a property and is a source of data from your app or website","A data stream lives within an account and is the container for the data you collect from apps and sites","A data stream lives within Explore and, once defined, can be added to any exploration","A data stream lives within Reports and lets you segment and compare your data"],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>GA4 hierarchy:</strong> Account → Property → Data Stream. A data stream is the 'pipe' that feeds data into a property. Three types: Web, iOS, and Android. Multiple streams can exist in one property for cross-platform tracking. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> The direct parent is the Property, not Account. Explore and Reports are analysis tools — not where streams are defined." },

  { id:13, cat:"Integrations & APIs",
    q:"If you wanted to gain insights into the organic search queries that are taking users to your website, which platform should you connect with Analytics?",
    opts:["Search Console","Search Ads 360","Google Ads","Firebase"],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>Search Console integration</strong> is the only way to see what users searched for on Google before clicking your site. It brings 'pre-click' data (queries, impressions, position). After linking, you must <em>publish the 'Search Console' collection</em> in the Library to see the reports. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Google Ads tracks paid keywords. Search Ads 360 is for large-scale paid campaigns. Firebase is for mobile apps." },

  { id:14, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"Which of these sections of Google Analytics Reports provides insights into where users are coming from (e.g., social media) before visiting your website?",
    opts:["Monetization","Acquisition","Demographics","Engagement"],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>Acquisition</strong> answers 'How do people find me?' Contains: User Acquisition (first-time discovery source) and Traffic Acquisition (ongoing session sources). <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Engagement = what users do on-site. Monetization = revenue data. Demographics = who the users are (country, age, gender) — not which channel brought them." },

  { id:15, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"You need to review several sets of data and decide to create a table report so you can see them side by side. Which component of the Analytics interface helps you do that?",
    opts:["The Date Picker component","The Filters component","The Comparisons component","The Segments component"],
    ans:2,
    exp:"<strong>Comparisons</strong> lets you view different subsets of data side by side in standard reports with color-coded labels. Comparisons persist as you navigate between different standard reports. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Filters remove data (don't show it side by side). Segments are for Explore only — not available in standard Reports. Date Picker = time-based comparison only, not user segment comparison." },

  { id:16, cat:"Integrations & APIs",
    q:"To link a Google Analytics property to BigQuery, you'll see two options for how frequently that data should be exported. What are those two options?",
    opts:["The two options are Hourly and Streaming.","The two options are Daily and Weekly.","The two options are Weekly and Streaming.","The two options are Daily and Streaming."],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Daily:</strong> Batch export — full file of all raw unsampled data from the previous day. Free for standard users (up to 1M events/day). <br><strong>Streaming:</strong> Near real-time, data appears within minutes. Small additional Google Cloud cost (~$0.05/GB). <br><br>'Fresh Daily' is a GA4 360-exclusive option. 'Hourly' and 'Weekly' are not available." },

  { id:17, cat:"Events, Audiences & Conversions",
    q:"When a user watches a video, this triggers an event on your website. Which of these is an event parameter?",
    opts:["The devices users are on when watching a video on your site","How many users viewed a video on your site","How many users opened the page containing a video on your site","Name of a video watched on your site"],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Event parameters</strong> provide context about a specific event. For video events (video_start, video_progress), GA4 auto-collects: <code>video_title</code> (name), <code>video_url</code>, <code>video_duration</code>, <code>video_percent</code>. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Device type = a session/user dimension. 'How many users' = a Metric (quantity). 'Users who opened the page' = a page_view metric." },

  { id:18, cat:"Advanced & 360",
    q:"Which Analytics 360 feature would you use to create a new data set by combining data from multiple source properties to get a broad view across brands, products, or regions?",
    opts:["Subproperties","Data streams","Organizations","Roll-up properties"],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Roll-up properties (360 only)</strong> aggregate data from multiple source properties into one single property for a comprehensive 'big picture' view. GA4 also attempts to de-duplicate users recognized across source properties. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Subproperties filter one property down (opposite). Data streams are individual collection pipes. Organizations manage billing/users — don't aggregate analytics data." },

  { id:19, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"Your colleague has customized a report and wants it to be easily viewable. Where should they add the report so it appears in the left-hand navigation?",
    opts:["Add it to Collection.","Add it to Explore.","Add it to Admin.","Add it to Library."],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>Collections</strong> are the display shelves of the left-hand nav. Reports are saved to the Library (storage), then must be added to a Collection and that Collection must be <em>Published</em> to appear in the sidebar. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Library = storage only (won't auto-appear in nav). Explore = separate advanced workspace. Admin = backend configuration." },

  { id:20, cat:"Events, Audiences & Conversions",
    q:"Which of the following scopes would be set for a custom dimension reporting membership status for a customer rewards program?",
    opts:["The Item scope would be set.","The Event scope would be set.","The Session scope would be set.","The User scope would be set."],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>User scope</strong> is for persistent attributes that describe the person, not a specific action. Membership Status (Bronze/Silver/Gold) applies to all of that user's sessions until it changes. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Event scope = details about a single action. Session scope = describes one visit (~30 min). Item scope = strictly for product-specific e-commerce data (size, color of a shirt)." },

  { id:21, cat:"Events, Audiences & Conversions",
    q:"Which of these approaches for creating audiences for your eCommerce site would provide you with a predictive audience?",
    opts:["Users who made a purchase in the last 30 days","Users who are likely to purchase in the next seven days","Users who started checking out but didn't complete the purchase","Users who added items to their purchase wishlist"],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>Predictive audiences</strong> use machine learning to forecast future behavior (not past). 'Likely 7-day purchasers' is a core template. Other predictive options: Likely 7-day churning users, Predicted 28-day top spenders. Requires 1,000+ positive and 1,000+ negative samples over 28 days. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Last 30 days = static/historical. Checkout abandoners and wishlist = behavioral audiences based on specific event triggers." },

  { id:22, cat:"Events, Audiences & Conversions",
    q:"You want to set up a new event to trigger when visitors land on a particular page. Which option would you choose in the Google Analytics Events interface?",
    opts:["You would choose Modify event.","You would choose Mark as key event.","You would choose Create event.","You would choose Import event."],
    ans:2,
    exp:"<strong>Create event</strong> lets you trigger a new specific event based on an existing one — no code changes needed. Example logic: 'When a page_view occurs AND page_location contains homepage, fire a new event called view_homepage.' <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Modify event = changes/fixes an existing event. Mark as key event = a toggle after the event exists. Import event = brings in conversions from linked platforms like Google Ads." },

  { id:23, cat:"Explorations & Analysis",
    q:"You've noticed discrepancies in your Google Analytics property and are trying to troubleshoot. Which of the following dimensions can you use to help identify anomalies or potential issues?",
    opts:["OS version, operating system with version, key event.","Item name, device category, date.","Country, OS version, operating system with version.","Page path, screen resolution, item name."],
    ans:2,
    exp:"<strong>Environmental dimensions</strong> isolate technical issues: OS Version/Operating System reveals if a problem affects only specific platforms (e.g., iOS 17.4, Chrome v122). Country identifies regional CDN failures or privacy-regulation tracking blocks. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Key event = a symptom indicator, not a cause-finder. Item name = e-commerce dimension. Page path = useful for page-specific bugs but lacks technical environment context." },

  { id:24, cat:"Advanced & 360",
    q:"If you're a business owner who wants to analyze how users arrive at your website AND app, as well as user journeys across both platforms, what should you use?",
    opts:["Use Firebase.","Use Google Analytics 4 properties.","Use Universal Analytics properties.","Use Google Marketing Platform."],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>GA4 properties</strong> were built for cross-platform tracking. Web, iOS, and Android data streams all live in one property. GA4 uses an identical event-based model for websites and apps, enabling Path Explorations that visualize cross-platform user journeys. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Firebase = development platform for mobile app data collection only. Universal Analytics = old version, weak app tracking. Google Marketing Platform = brand umbrella for a suite of tools." },

  { id:25, cat:"Advanced & 360",
    q:"When you've enabled Ads Personalization for your property, but want specific events excluded, what happens with the data for those excluded events?",
    opts:["That data will only be available in the Advertising section","That data will only be available in the Reports and Explore sections","That data will only be used for measurement purposes","That data will only be used for audiences in Google Ads"],
    ans:2,
    exp:"<strong>Excluded events (NPA)</strong> are still collected and visible in reports and explorations for measurement/analysis. However, any audience built using this data becomes ineligible for export to Google Ads or DV360 for ad targeting. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> The data is not restricted to specific UI sections — the restriction is about how the data can be used (measurement vs. targeting). It certainly cannot be used for Google Ads audiences." },

  { id:26, cat:"Data Collection",
    q:"If you want to analyze events and users across your website as well as its separate apps for iOS and Android — how should you set up your account?",
    opts:["One property with one web data stream for your website and two app data streams, one for iOS and the other for Android","One property with a web data stream for your website and one property with two app data streams","One property with one web data stream for your website and one app data stream for your app","One property with a web data stream for your website and one property with an app data stream for your app"],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>One property, three streams</strong> is the correct setup. A single property allows GA4 to de-duplicate users across platforms and provide a unified cross-platform view. iOS and Android require separate streams due to their different technical SDKs. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Separate properties breaks cross-platform user stitching. Only one app stream would miss either iOS or Android users." },

  { id:27, cat:"Explorations & Analysis",
    q:"Which of these exploration techniques helps you visualize the steps your users take toward a key task or conversion and determine how well they're succeeding or failing at each step?",
    opts:["Segment overlap helps visualize these steps.","Funnel exploration helps visualize these steps.","Cohort explorations helps visualize these steps.","Free form helps visualize these steps."],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>Funnel exploration</strong> defines sequential steps and shows the % of users who move between each. It visualizes 'drop-off' points and supports Open Funnels (enter at any step) or Closed Funnels (must start at step 1). <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Segment overlap = how different user groups intersect. Cohort = behavior of groups over time. Free form = flexible blank canvas for custom tables, not step-by-step flows." },

  { id:28, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"To understand how many users are coming from various devices, you run a report showing this data per device over the past 30 days. What is 'device type' in this report?",
    opts:["A dimension","A user","A metric","An event"],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>A dimension</strong> is a descriptive text attribute that categorizes data (e.g., Mobile, Desktop, Tablet). Dimensions appear as the left-column labels in report tables. They give context to metrics. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> A metric = a quantitative measurement (e.g., '1,000 users'). An event = a specific interaction (page_view, click). A user = the individual visitor who has a device type — the category itself is the dimension." },

  { id:29, cat:"Explorations & Analysis",
    q:"You are in your Google Analytics property's Explore section. What exploration technique should you use to customize metrics and dimensions in a table format?",
    opts:["Free form","Segment overlap","Funnel exploration","Cohort explorations"],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>Free form</strong> is the most flexible Explore tool — a blank canvas for dragging and dropping any combination of dimensions and metrics. Supports Table, Line, Scatter, Bar, and Donut views. Allows filters, segments, and breakdowns. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Segment overlap = group intersection tool. Funnel = linear user journey. Cohort = time-based group analysis." },

  { id:30, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"As a business owner, you'd like to do a deeper breakdown and analysis of the data displayed in your standard table report. Which feature would help you do that?",
    opts:["Comparisons would help you do a deeper breakdown.","Secondary Dimension would help you do a deeper breakdown.","Breakdowns would help you do a deeper breakdown.","Filters would help you do a deeper breakdown."],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>Secondary Dimension</strong> adds a second descriptive layer to your table. Example: City (primary) + Device category (secondary) = each city broken into Mobile, Desktop, Tablet rows. Click the '+' icon next to the primary dimension column header to add. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Comparisons = shows two data sets side by side. Filters = removes data, doesn't add new layers. 'Breakdowns' is not a standard GA4 report feature name." },

  { id:31, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"You want to know how various ads work together on the path to conversions, so you decide to look at the Attribution Paths Report. Where in your GA4 property can you find this report?",
    opts:["To view the report, go to Advertising.","To view the report, go to Admin.","To view the report, go to Explore.","To view the report, go to Reports."],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>Advertising section</strong> is the dedicated workspace for conversion paths and attribution. The Attribution Paths report shows touchpoint sequences before conversion (Early/Mid/Late interactions) and allows comparison of attribution models (Data-driven vs. Last click). <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Reports = standard traffic/engagement summaries. Explore = custom ad-hoc analysis. Admin = backend settings only." },

  { id:32, cat:"Integrations & APIs",
    q:"What can Google Ads do with audiences from Google Analytics when these two services are linked?",
    opts:["Audiences can be used to adjust geotargeting of ad campaigns","Audiences can be used to see industry benchmarking data","Audiences can be used to target ad campaigns","Audiences can be contacted for customer research"],
    ans:2,
    exp:"<strong>Target ad campaigns</strong> — linking GA4 with Google Ads exports your GA4 audiences as remarketing lists. You can bid more aggressively on high-value users or exclude already-converted users. With Ads Personalization enabled, audiences sync automatically to Google Ads Audience Manager. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Geotargeting = set in Google Ads campaign settings directly. Benchmarking = a GA4-internal feature. Contacting individuals = prohibited by privacy regulations and Google's ToS." },

  { id:33, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"Your team needs to change the default primary dimension for the User Acquisition Report within their GA4 property. Which action can they take to accomplish this?",
    opts:["They can create an exploration with the new primary dimension.","They can use the customization feature to edit the built-in report.","They can select a new primary dimension.","They can add a custom dimension to the report."],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>Customization feature (pencil icon)</strong> — requires Editor or Admin permissions. Opens the Report Builder → Report Data → Dimensions → reorder list. The dimension at the top becomes the default. Save as 'Save changes to current report.' <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Creating an exploration = separate ad-hoc report, doesn't change the standard report. Selecting a dimension via dropdown = temporary for your session only. Adding a custom dimension = adds to available list but doesn't set it as default." },

  { id:34, cat:"Reports & Navigation",
    q:"Which dimension should you use to determine which sources, such as 'organic search' or 'referral,' are driving users to your website?",
    opts:["You should use Session primary channel group (Default Channel Group).","You should use Page title and screen class.","You should use Google Ads campaign.","You should use Session source / medium."],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Session source / medium</strong> provides the most specific breakdown: Source = specific origin (google, facebook.com, bing) + Medium = category of traffic (organic, referral, cpc). Together they give both the 'who' and the 'how.' <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Channel group = higher-level bucket, lacks specific source detail. Page title = engagement dimension (what they view, not how they arrived). Google Ads campaign = only tracks paid Google traffic." },

  { id:35, cat:"Explorations & Analysis",
    q:"Your team wants to monitor for any unexpected spikes or declines in traffic to your website. Which built-in Google Analytics function highlights these events?",
    opts:["Google AI highlights these events.","Data-driven attribution highlights these events.","Machine learning highlights these events.","Anomaly detection highlights these events."],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Anomaly detection</strong> is the specific GA4 feature that acts as an automated early warning system. It analyzes historical data to predict 'normal' ranges and flags outliers. It accounts for seasonality and day-of-week patterns. Results appear in Insights cards on the Home page. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Machine learning / Google AI = broad technologies (not the specific feature name). Data-driven attribution = assigns credit to marketing channels for conversions." },

  { id:36, cat:"Explorations & Analysis",
    q:"You create a new path exploration in Explore that you plan to share with a co-worker. Who can see this new path exploration by default?",
    opts:["Just you; but you can share it with the other users of the property in read-only mode.","Anyone in your property can access the new path exploration and make edits to it.","Just you; but you can share it with the other users of the property so they can make edits.","Anyone in your property can access the new path exploration in read-only mode."],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>Explorations are private by default</strong> — only the creator can see them. When you share, it becomes visible to all property users in <em>read-only mode</em>. Co-workers can view and adjust date/segments but cannot save changes to your original. To edit, they must duplicate it to create their own copy. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> GA4 does not support collaborative editing on explorations. The default state is always private — not shared/read-only." },

  { id:37, cat:"Data Collection",
    q:"If you have created a Google Analytics 4 property for your mobile app and website, how would Google Analytics measure and report distinct user interactions?",
    opts:["As hits","As views","As sessions","As events"],
    ans:3,
    exp:"<strong>Events</strong> are GA4's universal measurement unit. Every single interaction — page views, button clicks, purchases, video plays — is an event with parameters providing additional context. This model works identically for websites and mobile apps. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Hits = Universal Analytics (old) terminology. Views/Page views = now a specific type of event (page_view event). Sessions = a grouping of events, not the unit of measurement itself." },

  { id:38, cat:"Events, Audiences & Conversions",
    q:"Google Analytics has a lot of data about user interactions with a video. Which of these choices is a 'user property' collected by Google Analytics?",
    opts:["Name of the video users can watch on your site","The language preference of users watching the video on your site","How many users opened the page containing the video on your site","How many users watched the video on your site"],
    ans:1,
    exp:"<strong>User property</strong> = a static attribute that describes the person, consistent across sessions. Language preference (e.g., English, Spanish) is a characteristic of who the user is. GA4 auto-collects: Language, Country, Device Model. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Video name = an Event parameter (describes the specific action). 'How many users opened the page' = a Metric (count). 'How many watched' = also a Metric." },

  { id:39, cat:"Integrations & APIs",
    q:"When Google Analytics and Google Ads are linked, how can Google Ads use conversion events from Google Analytics?",
    opts:["It can optimize bids for ad placements.","It can highlight industry benchmarking data.","It can adjust and optimize ad copy.","It can generate new keyword ideas."],
    ans:0,
    exp:"<strong>Optimize bids (Smart Bidding)</strong> — GA4 Key Events imported into Google Ads enable Smart Bidding to automatically adjust bids in real-time, bidding more aggressively for users who 'look like' past converters. Creates a feedback loop optimizing spend toward actual business results. <br><br><strong>Why others are wrong:</strong> Benchmarking = a GA4-internal research tool. Ad copy = must be edited manually. Keyword ideas = come from Keyword Planner, not the GA4 link." },

